# Drain-aware leader step-down — single-node

Single-node Bully claims self as leader (no higher peers).  Then
`setDraining(true)` releases leadership: `currentLeader()` returns
the empty string, and a follow-up `electLeader()` re-claims it once
the app un-drains.  Multi-node behaviour (peer takes over the
lease, leader drains for graceful restart) is exercised by the
integration suite; this test pins the local step-down across
INT/JS/JVM.

```scalascript
runActors {
  electLeader()
  println("leaderBefore='" + currentLeader() + "'")
  setDraining(true)
  println("draining=" + isDraining())
  println("leaderAfter='" + currentLeader() + "'")
  println("ok")
}
```
